(Athlete, 30 Oct 2011)'), ('Debut', '2002 for Republic of Korea (Athlete, 30 Oct 2011)'), ('Coach', 'Hong Seung Jin [club], KOR; Kim Seong Hoon [national], KOR (news.sbs.co.kr, 16 Apr 2018; thedailystar.net, 01 Dec 2017)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning team gold at the 2004 Olympic Games in Athens and 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing. (Athlete, 30 Oct 2011)'), ('Awards', 'In 2017 he was presented with Best Archer Award by the Korea Archery Association. (beffreport.com, 06 Feb 2018)In 2011 and 2012 he received a New Record Award by the Korea Archery Association. (osen.mt.co.kr, 15 Feb 2012; news.mk.co.kr, 25 Jan 2013)'), ('Additional Information', 'Draw weight42lbs (worldarchery.org, 22 Oct 2017)GeneralREDUCED VISIONHe has 20/100 vision in his right eye and 20/200 in his left eye. Despite his reduced vision he does not wish to wear glasses or contact lenses. "With my vision, when I look at the target, it looks as if different colour paints have been dropped in water. The boundaries are not that clear and the lines between the colours are very blurred. I\'ve practised using glasses before but actually it makes me feel less comfortable when I shoot. When I look down the range at the target all I can do is try to distinguish between the different colours. If I couldn\'t see the colours, now that would be a problem." (acbvi.org, 2012; news.bbc.co.uk, 2012)YOUNGESTHe became the youngest male archer to win a gold medal at an Olympic Games, when he was part of the Korean men\'s team that took gold at the 2004 Games in Athens, at age 18 years, 101 days. (nbcolympics.com, 18 Jul 2008; SportsDeskOnline, 24 Apr 2018) '), ('Hero', 'The members of the Korean archery team at the 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta. (olympic.org, 02 Nov 2011)'), ('Influence', 'His teachers, parents and friends. (Athlete, 30 Oct 2011)'), ('Relatives', 'His wife Lee Young Ji competed in archery, and represented Republic of Korea at the 2004 Junior World Championships in Lilleshall, England. (sports.donga.com, 04 Aug 2012)'), ('Nickname', 'Global Ace, Blind Archer, Hyun. (archery.org, 19 Apr 2010; BBC, 15 Aug 2011; World Archery, 16 Jul 2012)'), ('Injuries', 'In February 2011 he underwent surgery to remove a tumour between his cheekbone and eye. He returned to competitive action in July 2011. (kookbang.dema.mil.kr, 05 Jan 2013)He struggled with a shoulder injury in 2011 and underwent surgery. name: KYUNSUB
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began riding horses in his sixth year of primary school. (zum.com, 24 May 2013)'), ('Reason', 'He was encouraged to take up the sport by his grandfather, who was a former horse rider. (zum.com, 24 May 2013)'), ('Awards', 'He was named the 2012 Rider of the Year by the Korea Equestrian Federation. (yonhapnews.co.kr, 18 Dec 2012) In 2011 he received an Excellence Award at the Forum of Horse Riders in the Republic of Korea. (yonhapnews.co.kr, 12 Dec 2011)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralUNCLE\'S DEATHHis uncle Kim Hyung-Chil represented the Republic of Korea in equestrian and taught him how to ride. The pair were close and Kyun-Sub was deeply affected when his uncle died after being thrown from his horse at the 2006 Asian Games in Doha, Qatar. He was unable to ride for six months, but eventually returned to the sport and won gold in team dressage at the Asian Games in 2010 and 2014. "My uncle was my teacher, and he was like my father, too. I considered retirement after his death, but I returned to the sport in order to win a gold medal for him. Everything I do on a horse I learned from him. Every time I ride I think of him." (india.com, 20 Sep 2014; e2news.com, 29 Nov 2010)FURTHER EDUCATIONHe has studied for a graduate degree in physical education at Dankook University in Yongin, Republic of Korea. (Facebook profile, 28 Jul 2018) '), ('Influence', 'His father. (incheonilbo.com, 09 Oct 2016)'), ('Relatives', 'His grandfather Kim Cheol-Gyu represented the Republic of Korea in equestrian jumping at the 1964 Olympic Games in Tokyo, while his father Kim Sung-Chil was appointed president of the Incheon Equestrian Association in 2016. His uncle Kim Hyung-Chil was also a rider, winning silver in team eventing at the 2002 Asian Games in Busan, Republic of Korea. He died after he was thrown from his horse at the 2006 Asian Games in Doha, Qatar. (SportsDeskOnline, 07 Aug 2018; incheonilbo.com, 09 Oct 2016; news.joins.com, 28 Jul 2016; hankooki.com, 21 Oct 2010)'), ('Injuries', 'He suffered injuries to his neck and his back ahead of the 2016 National Sports Festival in the Republic of Korea, after a vehicle collided with his horse trailer. He went on to win a silver medal at the tournament, despite needing an injection in his back on the day of competition. (incheonilbo.com, 09 Oct 2016)'), ('Education', 'Physical Education - Kyungwon University, Seoul, KOR'), ('Languages', 'Korean'), ('Highlights', 'EQUESTRIAN EVENTINGRankEventYearLocationAsian Games2Eventing Team2002Busan, KOR6Eventing Individual2002Busan, KOREQUESTRIAN DRESSAGERankEventYearLocationAsian Games1Dressage Team2014Incheon, KOR1Dressage Team2010Guangzhou, CHN18Dressage Individual2014Incheon, KOR22Dressage Individual2010Guangzhou, CHNEQUESTRIAN JUMPINGRankEventYearLocationWorld Cup Chinese League4Jumping Individual2016/2017Gwacheon, KOR')]

She also won the individual time trial at the 2018 Asian Games to become the first athlete to have claimed gold in both events at the same edition of the Games. (SportsDeskOnline, 31 Aug 2018; asahi.com, 29 Aug 2018)NATIONAL FIRSTShe became the first female Korean cyclist to win an event at a round of the World Cup when she claimed a victory in the points race at the 2011/12 event in Astana, Kazakhstan. (jeollailbo.com, 28 Oct 2015; SportsDeskOnline, 02 Mar 2016; mbcsportsplus.com, 24 Nov 2017)'), ('Injuries', "She was knocked unconscious in a crash during the points race at the 2010 Asian Games in Guangzhou, People's Republic of China. name: JE ONE
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began cycling at age five and took up the sport seriously in Australia in 2006. (kbs.co.kr, 08 Aug 2014; news.chosun.com, 13 Aug 2014)'), ('Reason', 'He was encouraged by his father. (sportsworldi.com, 21 Dec 2017; ytn.co.kr, 10 Sep 2015)'), ('Debut', '2017 for Republic of Korea (kyongbuk.co.kr, 26 Jul 2017)'), ('Coach', 'Kim Young-Su [club], KOR; Um In-Young [national], KOR (national.sports.or.kr, 06 Nov 2017; kbmaeil.com, 04 Dec 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the Olympic Games. (ytn.co.kr, 10 Sep 2015)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralSANCTIONIn 2015, while living in Australia, he was handed a two-year competition ban by the Court of Arbitration for Sport and was stripped of his 2015 Junior World Championships sprint title after he was found guilty of using an intravenous drip of more than 50 millilitres following a 2014 race, which is prohibited under World Anti Doping Authority rules. The ruling in the case brought by the Australian Sports Anti-Doping Authority stated that there was no evidence he was using the drip to inject a prohibited substance, and he maintained that he did not know that using an intravenous drip was prohibited. His use of the intravenous drip was revealed when his sister posted a photo of him on her Facebook account. He returned to competition in May 2017. (kyongbuk.co.kr, 26 Jul 2017; asada.gov.au, 18 Apr 2016; jurisprudence.tas-cas.org, 17 Mar 2016) MOVE TO AUSTRALIAIn 2006 he moved to Australia with his parents in order to focus on training. (kbs.co.kr, 08 Aug 2014)'), ('Relatives', 'His father Park Jong-Hyun and his mother Choi Sim-Mi were both cyclists who represented the Republic of Korea at international competitions. name: SANGHOON
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up the sport in grade seven at Mokcheon Middle School in Cheonan, Republic of Korea. (sports-g.com, 01 Sep 2016; view.asiae.co.kr, 19 Jan 2017)'), ('Reason', 'He was influenced by his father. He joined the cycling team because he "wanted to enjoy cycling as a supplement to a diet". (news.joins.com, 22 Sep 2014; sports-g.com, 01 Sep 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Jang Yoon-Ho [club], KOR; Um In-Young [national], KOR; Jang Sun-Jae [national], KOR (newsmaker.or.kr, 14 Apr 2018; sports.news.naver.com, 21 Jun 2018; cycling.or.kr, 04 Jul 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (view.asiae.co.kr, 19 Jan 2017)'), ('Awards', 'In 2017, he was presented with a Cycling Grand Award by the Korea Cycling Federation. (yonhapnews.co.kr, 31 Jan 2018)In 2015, he was named Cyclist of the Year by the Korea Cycling Federation. (moneyweek.co.kr, 02 Feb 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralAPOLOGYBritish cyclist Mark Cavendish called him to apologise after a crash between the two during the omnium final at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. "He said sorry and told me that it was his fault for changing direction suddenly. He also sent a text message expressing his hope that I recover soon, and said that he wants to compete with me again. It was also my fault that I couldn\'t predict his movement. This kind of fall often happens in cycling. I\'m fine now." (sports-g.com, 01 Sep 2016)NATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first male Republic of Korea cyclist to win a gold medal at the Junior World Track Championships when he claimed a victory in the individual pursuit at the 2011 Worlds in Moscow, Russian Federation. (cyclingweekly.com, 18 Aug 2011; news.donga.com, 17 May 2016, SportsDeskOnline 31 Jul 2018) '), ('Hero', 'Coach Cho Ho-Sung. (news.donga.com, 17 May 2016)'), ('Influence', 'Cycling coach Cho Ho-Sung who convinced him to switch from the omnium to the individual pursuit. (stnsports.co.kr, 03 Jan 2016)'), ('Relatives', "His father Park Myung-Sun won a bronze medal for the Republic of Korea in the cycling road team event at the 1990 Asian Games in Beijing, People's Republic of China. He later became a cycling coach. (view.asiae.co.kr, 19 Jan 2017; news.joins.com, 22 Sep 2014)"), ('Injuries', 'He was carried off the velodrome on a stretcher during the omnium final at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro after a heavy crash with British cyclist Mark Cavendish. He escaped the incident with only bruises and Cavendish, the silver medallist in the event, accepted responsibility for the crash. (edition.cnn.com, 16 Aug 2016; sports-g.com, 01 Sep 2016; hani.co.kr, 16 Aug 2016; dailymail.co.uk 16 Aug 2016)In January 2016, he crashed during the omnium at the World Cup Series event in Hong Kong, China and was forced to withdraw from the competition. He required one month of rehabilitation to recover from his injuries. (yonhapnews.co.kr, 21 Jan 2016; sports-g.com, 01 Sep 2016)'), ('Education', 'Physical Education - Korea National Sport University, Seoul, KOR'), ('Languages', 'Korean'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationAsian Games2Team Pursuit2014Incheon, KOROlympic GamesDNFOmnium2016Rio de Janeiro, BRAWorld Championships14Omnium2017Hong Kong, CHN15Omnium2016London, GBRWorld Cup (Ranking)4Omnium2016/20174Omnium2015/201647Omnium2017/2018World Cup3Omnium2016/2017Los Angeles, CA, USA4Team Pursuit2017/2018Santiago, CHI4Omnium2015/2016Cambridge, NZL7Omnium2015/2016Cali, COL10Team Pursuit2017/2018Milton, ON, CAN11Omnium2016/2017Cali, COL17Omnium2017/2018Milton, ON, CANDNFOmnium2017/2018Santiago, CHIDNFOmnium2015/2016Hong Kong, CHNAsian Championships14000m Individual Pursuit2017New Delhi, IND1Madison2017New Delhi, IND14000m Individual Pursuit2015Nakhon Ratchasima, THA2Team Pursuit2017New Delhi, IND3Team Pursuit2015Nakhon Ratchasima, THA5Omnium2014Astana, KAZUCI Ranking (as of 07 Aug 2018)147Omnium2018/2019')]
